05637nam a22007575i 9780887555770DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875557707 a10.1515/97808875557702doi  a(DE-B1597)664635  a(OCoLC)1408682613  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aF1064.5.W7bR673 2019eb 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a971.27/430049242231 aRoss, Arthur, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommunal Solidarity :bImmigration, Settlement, and Social Welfare in Winnipeg’s Jewish Community, 1882–1930 /cArthur Ross. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Immigration and Culture ;v1600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tJewish Life in the Pale of Settlement -- tSocial Welfare and Communal Governance -- tJewish Immigration and Settlement in Winnipeg -- tGovernment Charitable Assistance and the Emergence of Jewish Social Welfare -- tCommunal Charity, Mutual Aid, and International Relief -- tWinnipeg’s Jewish Social Welfare Institutions -- t“Opening the Door”: The Western Division of the Jewish Immigrant Aid Society -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1882 and 1930 approximately 9,800 Jewish immigrants from Eastern Europe settled in Winnipeg. Newly arrived Jewish immigrants began to establish secular mutual aid societies, organizations based on egalitarian principles of communal solidarity that dealt with the pervasive problem of economic insecurity by providing financial relief to their members. The organization of mutual aid societies accelerated the development of a vibrant secular public sphere in Winnipeg’s Jewish community in which decisions about the provision of social welfare were decided democratically based on the authority and participation of the people. Communal Solidarity: Immigration, Settlement, and Social Welfare in Winnipeg’s Jewish Community, 1882–1930 looks at the development of Winnipeg’s Jewish community and the network of institutions and organizations they established to provide income assistance, health care, institutional care for children and the elderly, and immigrant aid to reunite families. Communal solidarity enabled the Jewish community to establish and sustain a system of social welfare that assisted thousands of immigrants to adjust to an often inhospitable city and build new lives in Canada. Arthur Ross’s study of the formation of Winnipeg’s Jewish community is not only the first history of the societies, institutions, and organizations Jewish immigrants created, it reveals how communal solidarity shaped their understanding of community life and the way decisions should be made about their collective future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity lifezManitobaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCommunity lifezManitobaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunity lifezManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy19th century. 0aCommunity lifezManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszManitobaxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantszManitobaxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantszManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxServices forzManitobay19th century. 0aJewsxServices forzManitobay20th century. 0aJewsxServices forzManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewsxServices forzManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszManitobaxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszManitobaxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszManitobaxSocial condi